WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.145 --> 00:00:01.795
Welcome to the Explainer.

2
00:00:02.005 --> 00:00:03.755
Today we're gonna talk about how millions

3
00:00:03.755 --> 00:00:06.355
of people experience the web, but not by sight.

4
00:00:06.605 --> 00:00:07.875
We're talking about sound.

5
00:00:08.085 --> 00:00:11.475
We're diving into the world of screen readers. Okay?

6
00:00:11.535 --> 00:00:13.155
So what a sighted person sees

7
00:00:13.155 --> 00:00:15.275
and what a screen reader user actually hears.

8
00:00:15.465 --> 00:00:17.475
Well, they can be two totally different things.

9
00:00:17.775 --> 00:00:20.675
You've got this beautiful visual design on one side,

10
00:00:20.815 --> 00:00:22.995
but the screen reader, it's all about the plain

11
00:00:23.025 --> 00:00:24.075
text you see on the other.

12
00:00:24.495 --> 00:00:26.195
And the thing that connects these two worlds,

13
00:00:26.415 --> 00:00:27.915
that's the accessibility tree.

14
00:00:28.385 --> 00:00:30.835
Yeah. A screen reader doesn't see your design

15
00:00:30.835 --> 00:00:32.275
and the way you and I do, it doesn't

16
00:00:32.275 --> 00:00:33.395
care about the colors or the layout.

17
00:00:33.745 --> 00:00:35.355
Instead, it reads the code,

18
00:00:35.355 --> 00:00:37.155
that underlying structure we just mentioned,

19
00:00:37.215 --> 00:00:38.475
the accessibility tree.

20
00:00:38.935 --> 00:00:41.715
And what it does is it announces the key info

21
00:00:41.715 --> 00:00:42.755
for every single element.

22
00:00:43.015 --> 00:00:46.115
You know its name, its role, is it a button, a link?

23
00:00:46.335 --> 00:00:48.715
And it's state like is it checked or disabled?

24
00:00:49.455 --> 00:00:51.115
So how does someone actually get

25
00:00:51.115 --> 00:00:52.275
around the page with this thing?

26
00:00:52.505 --> 00:00:55.075
It's not just one simple method on a desktop.

27
00:00:55.165 --> 00:00:57.515
Users have two completely different modes

28
00:00:57.615 --> 00:00:59.035
for two very different tasks.

29
00:00:59.615 --> 00:01:02.435
And honestly, getting your head around this is probably one

30
00:01:02.435 --> 00:01:04.435
of the most important concepts for understanding

31
00:01:04.455 --> 00:01:05.635
how screen readers work.

32
00:01:06.255 --> 00:01:08.475
And this right here, this is the core idea.

33
00:01:08.855 --> 00:01:11.395
You've got browse mode, which is for well browsing,

34
00:01:11.415 --> 00:01:12.875
you're reading, you're scanning.

35
00:01:13.245 --> 00:01:16.915
Think of it like reading a book. Then you have focus mode.

36
00:01:17.095 --> 00:01:18.195
That's for interacting

37
00:01:18.195 --> 00:01:20.195
with things like when you need your keyboard

38
00:01:20.335 --> 00:01:22.115
to actually type inside a form field.

39
00:01:22.335 --> 00:01:24.915
That's focus mode. And screen readers are

40
00:01:25.115 --> 00:01:26.195
actually really smart about this.

41
00:01:26.505 --> 00:01:28.235
They give you these little audio cues,

42
00:01:28.235 --> 00:01:29.715
so you always know which mode you're in.

43
00:01:30.185 --> 00:01:32.835
Take NVDA, A really popular one for Windows.

44
00:01:33.295 --> 00:01:35.995
It plays a little high pitch tone when you land in a form

45
00:01:35.995 --> 00:01:38.995
field that tells you, okay, you're in focus mode now,

46
00:01:39.215 --> 00:01:41.315
and when you leave, you get a low pitch tone.

47
00:01:41.655 --> 00:01:42.995
All right, you're back in browse mode.

48
00:01:43.705 --> 00:01:46.115
Okay, so knowing that these two modes exist, it kind

49
00:01:46.115 --> 00:01:47.355
of raises a big question, right?

50
00:01:47.575 --> 00:01:49.795
How do people actually use them to navigate a page?

51
00:01:50.095 --> 00:01:51.195
Do they just start at the very top

52
00:01:51.255 --> 00:01:53.595
and listen to every single word all the way to the bottom?

53
00:01:54.095 --> 00:01:58.035
The answer to that is a huge resounding no, absolutely not.

54
00:01:58.255 --> 00:01:59.715
And the data on this is wild.

55
00:01:59.775 --> 00:02:00.835
It will completely change

56
00:02:00.855 --> 00:02:02.475
how you think about designing a webpage.

57
00:02:02.735 --> 00:02:05.875
It turns out that less than 4%, 4%

58
00:02:06.135 --> 00:02:08.275
of screen reader users actually read a page

59
00:02:08.475 --> 00:02:09.555
straight through from top to bottom.

60
00:02:10.055 --> 00:02:13.835
And this chart, this is the big aha moment according to tons

61
00:02:13.835 --> 00:02:15.315
of survey data from web aim.

62
00:02:15.345 --> 00:02:18.835
Look at that over two thirds of screen reader users find

63
00:02:18.835 --> 00:02:20.755
what they're looking for by jumping from

64
00:02:20.775 --> 00:02:21.875
one heading to the next.

65
00:02:22.375 --> 00:02:24.915
That's it. That is their number one way of getting around.

66
00:02:25.415 --> 00:02:28.395
So here's the absolute key takeaway. Your heading structure.

67
00:02:28.545 --> 00:02:30.355
It's not just some nice to have

68
00:02:30.355 --> 00:02:32.235
for SEO for screen reader users.

69
00:02:32.375 --> 00:02:33.635
It is the navigation system.

70
00:02:33.865 --> 00:02:35.715
It's how they build a mental map of your page.

71
00:02:35.995 --> 00:02:38.155
A power user isn't gonna arrow down through everything.

72
00:02:38.265 --> 00:02:40.555
They're just gonna hit the H key to jump from heading

73
00:02:40.655 --> 00:02:42.475
to heading to heading HH.

74
00:02:42.815 --> 00:02:45.835
That's it. And this idea of navigating by structure,

75
00:02:46.025 --> 00:02:47.275
it's not just a desktop thing.

76
00:02:47.465 --> 00:02:50.195
It's absolutely crucial on mobile too, even though

77
00:02:50.195 --> 00:02:51.515
how it works is a little bit different.

78
00:02:51.975 --> 00:02:55.435
So on your phone screen, readers like voiceover on iOS

79
00:02:55.575 --> 00:02:58.675
or talkback on Android are basically always

80
00:02:58.775 --> 00:02:59.775
In browse node.

81
00:02:59.825 --> 00:03:01.885
You don't have that whole mode switching thing going on.

82
00:03:02.305 --> 00:03:05.205
And instead of keyboard shortcuts, it's all about gestures.

83
00:03:05.505 --> 00:03:06.765
On an iPhone, for example,

84
00:03:07.205 --> 00:03:10.525
a user does this cool two finger twist gesture on the screen

85
00:03:10.915 --> 00:03:12.325
that brings up something called the

86
00:03:12.335 --> 00:03:13.445
rotor, which is like a menu.

87
00:03:13.835 --> 00:03:16.365
They can set it to headings and then just swipe up

88
00:03:16.385 --> 00:03:19.565
or down to jump from one to the next. Super efficient.

89
00:03:20.025 --> 00:03:21.045
So what does that mean for you?

90
00:03:21.385 --> 00:03:23.685
It means that the semantic foundation of your design,

91
00:03:23.795 --> 00:03:25.965
your headings, your landmarks, is just

92
00:03:25.965 --> 00:03:27.645
as critical on a tiny phone screen

93
00:03:27.745 --> 00:03:29.485
as it is on a huge desktop monitor.

94
00:03:29.795 --> 00:03:31.125
That rotor on iOS

95
00:03:31.125 --> 00:03:32.565
or the reading controls on Android,

96
00:03:32.715 --> 00:03:35.205
they're completely useless if there's no structure

97
00:03:35.225 --> 00:03:36.565
for them to navigate through.

98
00:03:36.985 --> 00:03:38.725
Now, Look, the goal here is not for you

99
00:03:38.725 --> 00:03:41.165
to become a screen reader expert overnight, not at all.

100
00:03:41.315 --> 00:03:43.325
It's about doing a simple check on your own work.

101
00:03:43.635 --> 00:03:45.245
It's about building empathy, not

102
00:03:45.245 --> 00:03:46.685
by pretending you have a disability,

103
00:03:46.865 --> 00:03:48.125
but by actually understanding

104
00:03:48.185 --> 00:03:50.005
how the tool works with the thing you built.

105
00:03:50.665 --> 00:03:53.765
So here is a super simple actionable test you can do.

106
00:03:54.275 --> 00:03:57.285
Like right now, just turn on your computer's built in screen

107
00:03:57.285 --> 00:03:58.645
reader, go to your page

108
00:03:58.745 --> 00:04:01.045
and just press the H key again and again.

109
00:04:01.315 --> 00:04:02.645
Does it jump you through the content

110
00:04:02.825 --> 00:04:04.005
in a way that makes sense?

111
00:04:04.515 --> 00:04:06.325
Then pull up the elements list.

112
00:04:06.355 --> 00:04:07.565
It's just a keyboard shortcut,

113
00:04:07.745 --> 00:04:09.645
and that will show you a complete outline

114
00:04:09.645 --> 00:04:10.845
of all the headings on your page.

115
00:04:11.705 --> 00:04:13.165
And when you're looking at that list,

116
00:04:13.395 --> 00:04:15.405
just ask yourself this one simple question,

117
00:04:16.035 --> 00:04:18.445
does this list look like a logical table

118
00:04:18.445 --> 00:04:19.605
of contents for the page?

119
00:04:19.825 --> 00:04:21.565
Or is it just a flat confusing mess?

120
00:04:21.875 --> 00:04:23.845
Seriously, if you can answer that question,

121
00:04:23.845 --> 00:04:25.245
you'll catch the single biggest

122
00:04:25.345 --> 00:04:27.365
and most common navigation problem out there.

123
00:04:27.775 --> 00:04:30.365
Doing this simple test really moves you from only seeing

124
00:04:30.365 --> 00:04:32.165
your design to truly hearing it,

125
00:04:32.265 --> 00:04:33.645
and that is a fundamental shift.

126
00:04:33.985 --> 00:04:36.245
It helps make sure that what you create isn't just pretty,

127
00:04:36.545 --> 00:04:38.605
but that it actually works for everyone.

128
00:04:39.025 --> 00:04:40.725
So the question I wanna leave you with is this.

129
00:04:41.075 --> 00:04:42.765
What will your design sound like?
